             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am servant to Mr. Riollay; he lives at <placeName id="t17900526-34-crimeloc162">No. 17, Hart street, Bloomsbury</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17900526-34-crimeloc162" type="placeName" value="No. 17, Hart street, Bloomsbury"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17900526-34-crimeloc162" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17900526-34-off161 t17900526-34-crimeloc162"></join>. The prisoner knocked at the door, with Miss Hughes's compliments to Mrs. Riollay, and she had been very poorly lately, and would call on the morrow, as she was got better; I went in to deliver the message; he came between seven and eight; it was day-light; we had a light in the hall, and candles; he took a great coat, and two silk handkerchiefs.</p>
               <p>Mr. Garrow. I have no objection, my lord, to the jury finding him guilty, as he<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179005260037"></xptr>has been convicted of one felony already. The value of the coat was ten shillings.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17900526-34-verdict163" type="verdictDescription">
